<HEADLINE>
BANKS REQUIRED TO DISCLOSE DEFAULTERS ON LOANS OVER NT$100
MILLION
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei, March 7 (CNA) 03/07/07  16:43:32 (By Lilian Wu)
</P>
<P>
Premier Su Tseng-chang said Wednesday that domestic banks should
disclose in April every year the names of defaulters on loans
over NT$100 million (US$3.03 million) in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The premier made the remarks after an Executive Yuan meeting in
which the Financial Supervisory  Commission  gave a report on
publishing the information on defaulters according to the Banking
Act.
</P>
<P>
As a warm-up, banks are required to disclose March 15 the
information of defaulters on bank loans over NT$100 million as of
the end of June 2006, Su said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Banking Act protects the privacy of bank
customers, but said the public interest should also be protected.
</P>
